CONFIRMED TRAP INSTANCES — JUNE 2024
(Source: Pearson WMA12/01 June 2024 Examiner Report)

These errors were explicitly named by the principal
examiner. Treat as highest-priority traps.

BINOMIAL — NEGATIVE SIGN DROPPED (Q1a)
Missing negative from coefficient of x in (1–x/6)^9
→ M awarded, A lost for that term

BINOMIAL — UNSIMPLIFIED FINAL TERM (Q1a)
Question says "simplest form" → all terms must be
fully simplified → A lost if not

BINOMIAL — DECIMAL NOT EXACT RECURRING (Q1b)
8.83 instead of 8.8̄3̄ = lose final A
Rule: recurring decimal must be stated as exact
recurring, not rounded

ARITHMETIC SERIES — WRONG n IN FORMULA (Q2a)
Using u₆ = 6 instead of u₆ = 2 → B mark lost

SERIES — NOT ROUNDING UP (Q2b)
n = 34.2 or n = 34 instead of n = 35 → A0
Rule: smallest INTEGER satisfying inequality →
always round UP, never truncate or truncate-round

LOG LAW — DISTRIBUTING OVER BRACKETS (Q3i)
log(2–x) treated as log2 – logx = 0 marks for
that step. Fundamental error, no M credit.

LOG LAW — COMBINING WITHOUT POWER LAW FIRST (Q3i)
Attempting to combine before applying 2log → log(...)²
→ M lost for combination step

LOG EQUATION — WRONG ROOT SELECTED (Q3i)
x = 26 accepted without domain check → A lost
x = –6 is the ONLY valid answer
Rule: both roots must be checked; wrong root = A lost

FACTOR THEOREM — "=0" NOT SHOWN (Q4b)
"Show that k = 11": f(½) substituted without
explicitly writing f(½) = 0 → A1* lost
The "= 0" must be stated, not implied

FACTORISATION — NOT ONE EXPRESSION (Q4c-i)
Finding factors separately without stating
f(x) = (2x–1)(x²+x+1) as a single expression
→ final A mark lost

DISCRIMINANT — INEQUALITY NOT STATED (Q4c-ii)
Computing b²–4ac = –3 but NOT writing –3 < 0
→ A mark lost
Must state: (1) calculated value, (2) inequality
< 0, (3) therefore no real roots

PROOF — DIVISION WITHOUT REASONING (Q5a)
Dividing by 3xy without stating "x and y are
positive so 3xy > 0, inequality direction preserved"
→ final A1* lost

COUNTER-EXAMPLE — BOTH VALUES POSITIVE (Q5b)
Choosing x = 3, y = 1 (both positive) = M0
Must have positive x and NEGATIVE y (e.g. x=3, y=–1)

TRAPEZIUM RULE — h FROM FORMULA NOT TABLE (Q6b)
Using h = (b–a)/n instead of reading consecutive
x-values from the table → B mark for h lost
June 2024: h = 0.3 (from x = 2, 2.3, 2.6, ...)

INTEGRATION — TRAPEZIUM RULE REUSED IN (c) (Q6c)
Applying trapezium rule again in Q6(c) = M0A0
Must use algebraic integration of the manipulated
expression, not a numerical method

CIRCLE — NOT SQUARE-ROOTING FOR RADIUS (Q7a)
(x+4)²+(y–5)²=70 → radius = √70 NOT 70 → A lost

CIRCLE PROOF — WRONG COMPARISON (Q7b)
Comparing d(centres) to ONE radius instead of
SUM of both radii → dM1 lost
Correct: if d(centres) > r₁ + r₂ → circles external

CIRCLE PROOF — NO DECIMAL VALUES (Q7b)
Stating √250 > √70+√52 without computing decimal
values (15.81 and 15.58) → A1* lost
Must show calculated decimal comparisons to support
the inequality conclusion

TRIGONOMETRY — INCOMPLETE cos x MULTIPLICATION (Q8i)
Multiplying most terms by cos x but missing the
constant 13 → quadratic not correctly formed
→ M and A lost for that step

TRIGONOMETRY — DEGREES FOR RADIAN ANSWER (Q8i)
Answer required in radians → working in degrees
and converting late: M marks preserved, A marks
lost for wrong numerical answers
Required: x = 1.91 radians

TRIG MODELLING — OMITTING SECOND k VALUE (Q8ii-a)
Finding k = 6.41 but omitting k = 17.59 → one A
mark lost. Both values in range must be stated.

TRIG MODELLING — TIME NOT CONVERTED (Q8ii-c)
Getting t = 11.23 (hours) without converting to
11:14 (time of day) → A mark lost
Contextual question requires contextual answer

FRACTIONAL POWERS — SQUARING TO SOLVE (Q9a)
Squaring dy/dx = 0 to get 144x–25x³ = 0 (incorrect)
instead of factoring out x^(1/2) → A0
Correct: factor x^(1/2) from 12x^(1/2) – 5x^(3/2)
= 0 → x^(1/2)(12–5x) = 0

EQUAL AREAS — WRONG SIGN IN EQUATION (Q9b)
Setting R₂ integral equal to +1024/35 instead of
–1024/35 (R₂ is below x-axis) → dM mark lost
Correct: ∫₀ᵏ y dx = 0 → (16/5)k^(5/2) –
(4/7)k^(7/2) = 0 → k = 28/5

GP MODELLING — INDEXING ERROR (Q10)
Value after n years = ar^n confused with nth term
ar^(n–1) → A marks lost for incorrect index
MS allowed M marks for correct method with wrong
index — VERIDIAN awards same way

GP MODELLING — NO EQUATION FOR N (Q10b)
Finding correct a and b but not writing N = ab^t
→ final A mark lost. Must be an equation.

